{{Quote|You were at Serroco, when they turned the Stereb cities into glass craters.|[[Atton Rand]], to Meetra Surik|<ref name="kotorII">''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic II: The Sith Lords]]''</ref>}}
'''Serroco''', the [[Homeworld/Legends|homeworld]] of the [[Stereb]] [[Species/Legends|species]], was a [[Planet/Legends|planet]] in the [[Ploo sector/Legends|Ploo sector]] of the [[Expansion Region/Legends|Expansion Region]]. A muddy world, Serroco was constantly buffeted by ferocious storms and [[tornado]]es that often forced the Stereb to retreat to underground shelters and catacombs. The world was dotted by the grand stone [[Stereb cities]] and newer settlements populated by [[Human/Legends|Humans]] from the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]]. Serroco was a full member of the Republic, and when the [[The galaxy/Legends|galactic]] government went to [[Mandalorian Wars|war]] with the [[Mandalorian/Legends|Mandalorian]] warrior clans in [[3963 BBY]], the planet became a flashpoint in the growing conflict.

[[Admiral/Legends|Admiral]] [[Saul Karath]], anticipating a Mandalorian advance on the planet, rounded up a sizable [[Battle Group Serroco|battle group]] to defend Serroco and placed camps among the Stereb [[City/Legends|cities]]. Disdainful of the location of the camps and seeing it as a dishonorable approach, the Mandalorians [[Battle of Serroco|nuclear-bombed]] the planet directly when their force arrived at Serroco, destroying the cities entirely. One [[Republic Navy/Legends|Republic Navy]] [[Pilot/Legends|pilot]], [[Carth Onasi]], saved many Stereb lives by calling down false tornado warnings and sending them to their underground shelters, which shielded them from the blasts. Life on Serroco continued on despite the devastation of the planet, and a [[Republic Military/Legends|Republic military]] presence was reestablished there by the [[Time/Legends|time]] of the [[Galactic War]] several [[Standard century/Legends|centuries]] later. By the [[Imperial Era/Legends|Imperial Period]], a small population of Stereb continued to exist on Serroco.

==Description==
[[File:Camp_Three_Socorro.jpg|thumb|left|250px|A Republic military camp located near a Stereb city on Serroco]]
{{Quote|Hard enough keeping clean in this mudhole without this stuff happening!|A Republic soldier, on Serroco, after a [[Service droid/Legends|serving droid]] spilled food on his uniform|<ref name="kotor14" />}}
Serroco was a muddy, [[Water/Legends|rainy]] [[Planet/Legends|world]]<ref name="kotor14" /> located in the [[Serroco system/Legends|Serroco system]] of the [[Expansion Region/Legends|Expansion Region's]] [[Ploo sector/Legends|Ploo sector]].<ref name="TEAOC" /> The [[Homeworld/Legends|homeworld]] of the [[Stereb]] [[Species/Legends|species]], Serroco had an [[Atmosphere/Legends|atmosphere]] that supported other [[Sentience/Legends|sentient]] life forms, such as [[Human/Legends|Humans]]. Expansive dirt fields could be found on the planet, with patches of [[Tree/Legends|trees]] and other [[Plant/Legends|plants]]. It rained frequently on Serroco, and bigger storms often broke out, with [[tornado]]es sometimes posing a threat to the Stereb.<ref name="kotor14" />

The planet had multiple continents<ref name="kotor14" /> and revolved around at least one [[Serroco (star)|star]]. Serroco's land appeared [[Color/Legends|green]] from [[Realspace/Legends|space]], with [[Ocean/Legends|oceans]] covering a large part of the planet's surface.<ref name="kotor15" /> The [[Mandalorian/Legends|Mandalorian]] [[Nuclear weapon/Legends|nuclear]] [[Battle of Serroco|attack]] on Serroco during the [[Mandalorian Wars]] between the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]] and the Mandalorian warrior clans had a great impact on the planet's landscape&mdash;the world's [[Stereb cities]] were destroyed,<ref name="kotor15" /> leaving only [[Glass/Legends|glass]] craters.<ref name="kotorII" />

==History==
{{Quote|Let them see what such a defense deserves. Let them burn.|[[Mandalore the Ultimate]]|<ref name="kotor14" />}}
By the [[Time/Legends|time]] of the Mandalorian Wars, Serroco was a full member of the Galactic Republic, and Human settlers from the Republic had put down roots on one of Serroco's nicer continents. The [[Republic Navy/Legends|Republic Navy]] maintained an [[Orbit/Legends|orbital]] [[Unidentified watchstation|watchstation]] above the stormy planet, issuing tornado warnings to the Stereb, who were not adept with the technology themselves. However, some personnel stationed at the watchstation found it to be a boring posting and amused themselves by calling in fake tornado warnings during festivals, sporting events, and other gatherings, a practice that ended when Serroco's [[Unidentified senator (Serroco)|senator]] complained.<ref name="kotor14" /> Multiple [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] were also regularly assigned to the planet&mdash;during the Mandalorian Wars, one of the Jedi on Serroco was the Human [[Meetra Surik]].<ref name="surik">In ''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic II: The Sith Lords]]'', the main character, [[Meetra Surik]], is mentioned as having been on Serroco at the [[Time/Legends|time]] of the [[Mandalorian/Legends|Mandalorian]] [[Battle of Serroco|attack]]. Since [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] involvement in the war had not yet begun, this was rectified by the later ''[[Galactic Republic Defense Ministry Daily Brief KD0092]]'', which says that there were Jedi on regular assignment to Serroco and one was able to get away on one of the few [[Starship/Legends|ships]] to escape. Logically, this would have to be Surik.</ref> In [[3963 BBY]], the Mandalorian warrior clans advanced on Serroco from the planet [[Jebble]]<ref name="TEA" />&mdash;anticipating an attack, [[Admiral/Legends|Admiral]] [[Saul Karath]] assembled [[Battle Group Serroco]] and set up a staging area on the planet, with encampments among the Stereb [[City/Legends|cities]]. The camps were home to a great number of Republic Navy personnel, in addition to [[Fringer/Legends|fringers]] [[Merchant/Legends|selling]] [[Foodstuff/Legends|food]] and other services to the [[Soldier/Legends|soldiers]]. [[Camp Three (Serroco)|Camp Three]] featured the extremely popular ''[[Little Bivoli]]'' mess [[Starship/Legends|ship]], which was run by two fugitives: [[Zayne Carrick]], a former Jedi [[Padawan/Legends|Padawan]] falsely accused of [[Padawan Massacre|murdering]] his entire class on [[Taris/Legends|Taris]], and [[Marn Hierogryph]], a petty criminal believed to be his accomplice. Despite being two of the most wanted beings in the Republic, Carrick and Hierogryph were able to evade notice right under the nose of Karath and his battle group.<ref name="kotor14" />

Karath and his team thought they were completely ready for the Mandalorians&mdash;they figured that the Mandalorians would not dare to attack the Stereb cities directly, for fear of wrecking potential loot. Karath set up a massive cordon of ships surrounding the planet, hoping to stop the Mandalorians dead in their tracks. On the planet below, however, Carrick had a [[Force vision/Legends|Force vision]] of the Mandalorians destroying the Stereb cities and annihilating the Republic camps, and he decided that he immediately needed to warn Karath.<ref name="kotor14" /> In a rush, Carrick stowed away on hotshot Republic [[Pilot/Legends|pilot]] [[Carth Onasi]]'s ship, the ''[[Deadweight]]'', convincing Onasi of his seriousness and hitching a ride with him to Karath's [[Bridge (starship)/Legends|bridge]] on the [[Warship/Legends|warship]] [[Courageous (Inexpugnable-class)|''Courageous'']]. There, Carrick was recognized as the so-called "Jedi killer" and accused of being a Mandalorian [[Spy/Legends|spy]]. His warnings went unheeded. Soon, a Mandalorian force came out of [[Hyperspace/Legends|hyperspace]] at the edge of the [[Star system/Legends|system]]. Disgusted by the Republic's "dishonorable" tactic of placing its camps so close to the Stereb cities, the invaders started off the proceedings by firing off nuclear [[Missile/Legends|missiles]]&mdash;to Karath's surprise, the missiles angled around the Republic ships, heading toward the Serroco camps. As Karath did not expect this to happen, the camps' missile defense systems were not online, and the planet was left defenseless.<ref name="kotor15" />

[[File:Nuclear_explosions.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The destruction of Serroco]]
Impacts were counted near twenty-seven populated areas. While the Human settlements sustained heavy damage, the Stereb cities were simply gone,<ref name="kotor15" /> turned into glass craters.<ref name="kotorII" /> Furthermore, only eight of the Republic ships on the surface escaped destruction,<ref name="kotor15" /> one of which carried the [[Jedi Knight/Legends|Jedi Knight]] Meetra Surik.<ref name="surik" /> Before the missiles were launched, Onasi had buzzed down tornado warnings to seventeen Stereb cities, hoping that their underground catacombs could protect them if Carrick's vision came true,<ref name="kotor15" /> an endeavor that saved many lives.<ref name="kotorhb">''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic Handbook]]''</ref> Serroco was nearly annihilated, its surface covered in massive craters where once had been cities and settlements.<ref name="kotor15" /> The Republic immediately condemned the destruction of Serroco as a tragedy and a horrific crime,<ref name="invasion">{{KOTORbackups|18}}</ref> and the devastation was not soon forgotten. Republic [[Propaganda/Legends|propagandist]] "[[Benegryph Goodvalor]]" chose ''Serroco'' as the name of his imaginary warship in transmissions aimed at the Mandalorians,<ref name="interference">{{Hyperspace|url=hyperspace/fiction/interference20090929.html|text="Interference"|int=Interference|newhost=Suvudu}}</ref> and the planet became the namesake of a real Republic [[Serroco (starship)|ship]] by the time of the later [[Galactic War]].<ref name="taral">{{TORcite|type=flashpoint|Taral V}}</ref> "Goodvalor" was actually Marn Hierogryph, who, along with talented [[Trandoshan/Legends|Trandoshan]] [[Chef/Legends|cook]] [[Slyssk]], had narrowly escaped Serroco's destruction on a stolen [[Troop/Legends|troop]] [[Transport/Legends|transport]], inadvertently saving half of a [[Sleep/Legends|sleeping]] [[Battalion/Legends|battalion]]. The Republic [[Ministry of Defense|Defense Ministry]] turned the rescue into a propaganda story, with "Goodvalor" being feted as the "Hero of Serroco."<ref name="kotor47">[[Knights of the Old Republic 47|''Knights of the Old Republic'' 47]]</ref>

Life on Serroco still continued, and by the time of the [[Jedi Civil War]] several [[Standard decade/Legends|decades]] after the Mandalorian conflict, Serroco had a leader named [[Lelin-Dor]], who was known as the [[First Patriarch]]. During the war, [[Revan/Legends|Revan]], the [[Dark Lord of the Sith/Legends|Dark Lord of the Sith]], had Lelin-Dor [[Assassin/Legends|assassinated]], believing him to be a destabilizing influence.<ref name="kotorII" /> By the time of the [[Cold War (Galactic Republic–Sith Empire)|Cold War]] a few [[Standard century/Legends|centuries]] later, a [[Republic Military/Legends|Republic military]] presence had been reestablished on Serroco.<ref name="iresso">{{TORcite|type=conversation|Felix Iresso|Command Decision}}</ref> In that same time period, [[Archaeology/Legends|archaeologists]] discovered an intact Stereb shelter left over from the Battle of Serroco, containing many previously-lost Stereb artifacts.<ref name="shelter">{{TORcite|type=crewskill|Archaeology|Under the Glass Desert}}</ref> During the [[Imperial Era/Legends|Imperial Period]], thousands of [[Standard year/Legends|years]] after the Battle of Serroco, there was still a small enclave of Stereb on the planet.<ref name="sword">{{DoD|Sword of the Empire}}</ref>

==Inhabitants==
[[File:Stereb.jpg|thumb|left|250px|A Stereb on Serroco]]
{{Quote|What&mdash;oh, you mean the Stereb cities?''"<br />"''The stone things.''"<br />"''They belong to the Stereb. They're those tall guys. This is their planet. Oh, there are human settlers from the Republic here, too&mdash;but they're on one of the nicer continents.|Carth Onasi and Zayne Carrick|<ref name="kotor14" />}}
Serroco was home to the Stereb species, who built the massive stone cities that dotted the planet's landscape. By the time of the Mandalorian Wars, however, Serroco had also been settled by Humans from the Republic, who lived on one of the planet's nicer continents. The Mandalorians' impending attack on Serroco also brought a significant population of Republic Navy personnel to the world, led by Admiral Saul Karath. Meant to defend the world from the Mandalorians, the soldiers lived in camps placed among the Stereb cities.<ref name="kotor14" />

There were also fringers,<ref name="kotor14" /> or freelance tradespeople,<ref name="jimas">{{KOTORbackups|13}}</ref> who also came to the world with the Navy to sell their goods and services. Notable among these beings were Zayne Carrick and Marn Hierogryph, two of the most wanted fugitives in the Republic, who sold food in Camp Three without attracting any notice. Even before the Battle of Serroco, there was a Republic [[Navy/Legends|naval]] presence above the planet, as it fell to the Republic to operate Serroco's orbital watchstation and alert the natives of dangerous weather. Bored crewmen often amused themselves by calling in fake tornado warnings, a practice that drew the ire of Serroco's [[Senator/Legends|senator]].<ref name="kotor14" />

==Locations==
[[File:GryphBivoli.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The popular ''Little Bivoli'' eatery, located in Serroco's Camp Three]]
{{Quote|We still haven't heard from anyone&mdash;but those catacombs go pretty deep. They used to live there. They can do it again.|Carth Onasi, after the Battle of Serroco|<ref name="kotor15" />}}
The Stereb built many stone cities across Serroco, with grand pyramidal buildings and large green columns rising from the earth, although they originally lived in underground catacombs,<ref name="kotor15" /> which the Stereb built to escape Serroco's vicious storms<ref name="cswe">{{CSWECite|III|140|Serroco}}</ref> and were still maintained as shelters during the era of the Mandalorian Wars. The Republic set up its camps amongst the Stereb cities in preparation for the Mandalorian attack. One of these, Camp Three, featured the ''Little Bivoli'' mess wagon run by Zayne Carrick and Marn Hierogryph. Boasting the talents of the Trandoshan cook Slyssk, the ''Little Bivoli'' became popular amongst Republic naval personnel who were tired of the food from the commissary. A watchstation was located in Serroco's orbit was operated by the Republic Navy to monitor the planet's weather.<ref name="kotor14" />

==Behind the scenes==
The planet Serroco was first mentioned in ''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic II: The Sith Lords]]'', a [[Star Wars video games|video game]] released in [[2004]]. The planet and its destruction at the hands of the Mandalorians were mentioned as part of the background of the game's main character, Meetra Surik<ref name="kotorII" />&mdash;they would not actually appear until ''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic: Days of Fear]]'', a [[Star Wars comic books|comic]] arc written by [[John Jackson Miller]] and released in [[2007]].<ref name="kotor14" /><ref name="kotor15" /> Serroco was mentioned in a number of [[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic (comic series)|''Knights of the Old Republic'']] issues<ref name="kotor31">[[Knights of the Old Republic 31|''Knights of the Old Republic'' 31]]</ref><ref name="kotor42">[[Knights of the Old Republic 42|''Knights of the Old Republic'' 42]]</ref> and in a number of other sources, such as Miller's novel [[Knight Errant (novel)|''Knight Errant'']],<ref name="errant">[[Knight Errant (novel)|''Knight Errant'']]</ref> the ''[[Star Wars: The Old Republic]]'' MMORPG,<ref name="iresso" /> ''[[The Essential Atlas]]'',<ref name="TEA" /> ''[[The Essential Guide to Warfare]]'',<ref name="egw">''[[The Essential Guide to Warfare]]''</ref> and an entry in ''[[The Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia]]''.<ref name="cswe" />

